Durban - A truck driver and his two assistants have been airlifted to hospital after the truck they were travelling in collided into a wall in Pinetown on Monday. Garrith Jamieson, Rescue Care Paramedics spokesperson, said the driver allegedly lost control of the truck and it veered off the road colliding into a building on Gillitts Road just after 7 am. "When we arrived on the scene we found three men all entrapped in the wreckage. Immediately Advanced Life Support Paramedics as well as Durban Fire Department was dispatched to assist on the scene. Due to the prolonged entrapment as well as the injuries sustained the Lenmed 1 Aeromedical Helicopter was activated to assist,"he said. Whilst the Durban Fire Department used the Jaws of Life and other hydraulic equipment to free the injured men Advanced Life Support Paramedics stabilised them. Once freed the men were transported to Lenmed Nu Shifa Hospital for the further care that they required. At this stage the events leading up to this crash is unknown however SAPS will be investigating further. Andreas Mathios, Blue Security spokesperson, said the recovery of the truck is in progress. "Durban Metro police have closed off the road temporarily.Â  The slight delay was because they were shifting the load of the truck to anther truck. Once it has been done they will upright it the truck and have it removed by Joeys Towing,"he said. Daily News